question_md:
Everyone knows the following situation: you want to assign a variable, but have to catch an exception, and in that case assign a fallback value.

This always results at least in a 6-liner, while you just want a simple fallback value and maybe don&#39;t care about the exception.

How can the following be optimized in terms for reading or boilerplate code, if possible?

```
            List&lt;String&gt; mylist;
            try {
                mylist = readFile(resource);
            } catch (Exception e) {
                mylist = List.of();
            }
```

I&#39;m looking for some kind of the following (which is of course pseudocode), but to illustrate what my goal is:

```
List&lt;String&gt; mylist = if (success) ? readFile(resource) : List.of();
```

answer_md:
If you don&#39;t want to add more libraries, you can use a helper method and define your own supplier interface throwing an exception.
```
@FunctionalInterface
public interface ThrowingSupplier&lt;T&gt; {

  T get() throws Exception;
}
```
The helper:
```
public class Helper {

  public static &lt;T&gt; T computeOrElse(ThrowingSupplier&lt;T&gt; computation, Function&lt;Exception, T&gt; errorHandler) {
    try {
      return computation.get();
    } catch (Exception exc) {
      return errorHandler.apply(exc);
    }
  }
}
```
The fallback error handler is a function accepting the exception - this gives you the flexibility to handle it however you want.

Example usages:
```
List&lt;String&gt; res = Helper.computeOrElse(() -&gt; readFile(resource), e -&gt; List.of());
List&lt;String&gt; res2 = Helper.computeOrElse(() -&gt; readFile(resource), e -&gt; {
  LOGGER.error(&quot;Could not read file, using fallback&quot;, e);
  return List.of();
});
List&lt;String&gt; res3 = Helper.computeOrElse(() -&gt; readFile(resource), e -&gt; {
  throw new RuntimeException(e);
});
```

